AGI - Locked for over nine months on the International Space Station (Iss), two astronauts > can hope to return home after the launch of a crew exchange mission. A Falcon 9 rocket from the company Space X>&nbsp; took off from the Kennedy Space Center, Florida, carrying a four-member team—directed to the orbital outpost. &nbsp;
Initially planned for Wednesday, the takeoff had been canceled at the last minute due to a technical problem to the ground support system. Since then an inspection and an "air bag" was carried out which probably caused the problem was evacuated, said Nasa.
This mission, called Crew 10, should allow Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams>, two American astronauts blocked in the International Space Station (ISS) from last June, to return to Earth. They could take this return next Wednesday, a few days after the arrival of the new crew, aboard a spaceship SpaceX - and not of the Boeing Starliner apparatus that had transported them and that had suffered failures.

